#=GF CC   LC3 Interacting Regions (LIRs), also known as ATG8-interacting
#=GF CC   motifs (AIMs), are short-linear motifs (SLiMs) of autophagy
#=GF CC   receptors and adaptor proteins that facilitates the selective
#=GF CC   recruitment of autophagy substrates to the autophagosome. ATG8
#=GF CC   proteins are highly conserved in eukaryotes and play a key role
#=GF CC   in selective autophagy as they recognise and bind different
#=GF CC   autophagy receptors and adaptors containing a specific class of
#=GF CC   SLiMs. LIRs are characterised by degenerated sequences with a
#=GF CC   four-residue core central sequence involved in ATG8-binding,
#=GF CC   with the W/Y/FxxL/I/V pattern. Based on the aromatic amino acid
#=GF CC   in position 1 they can be classified into W-type, Y-type and
#=GF CC   F-type. This entry is the F-type LIR motif from ATG4, which
#=GF CC   contains the seqeunce FEI/VL. There are acidic residues at the
#=GF CC   N-terminal of this motif (Asp and Glu), which may contribute to
#=GF CC   stabilize the binding or may provide specificity toward a
#=GF CC   certain class of ATG8 proteins [1].
